Stenamma saenzae
shows considerable morphological variability among populations. From this variation, I describe two variants that differ significantly from the type phenotype (indicated above). Variant 1 (Figure 147
A-C
) occurs mainly in central Guatemala (Biotopo Quetzal, 
Purulha
) and has the following distinguishing features: pronotal dorsum smooth and shiny; postpetiole more bulging, appearing larger than petiolar node; head somewhat enlarged. Although distinct from the type population, I find intermediate phenotypes at intervening localities, causing me to conclude that this variation is probably intraspecific, and likely due to environmental effects on size and sculpture. Supporting this view is the observation that the locality Biotopo Quetzal, where variant 1 is most distinct, is an especially cool, wet cloud forest site.
